07310nam a2200877Ia 9780231554145DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315541457 a10.7312/mint201522doi  a(DE-B1597)670310  a(OCoLC)1391442665  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQL76 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a590.73223/eng/2023020802aA Wilder Kingdom :bRethinking Nature in Zoos, Wildlife Parks, and Beyond /ced. by Ben A. Minteer, Harry Greene. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b25 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Zoos and the Wild: A Reconsideration -- t2. Between Worlds: A Conversation Among the Cranes -- t3. Animal Art and the Changing Meanings of the Wild -- t4. Can Zoos Connect People with Wildness? -- t5. “Wild” Through an American Indian Historical Analysis -- t6. Toward a Wilder Kin-Dom: Why Zoos Must Focus More on Ecological Interactions (with Our Children and Other Biota) Than on Isolated Species -- t7. This Is a Zoo? Reflections on a Wilder Zoo by Visitors to the Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum -- t8. Evolution to the Rescue: Natural Selection Can Help Captive Populations Adapt to a Changing World -- t9. Zoo Dogs -- t10. Zoo Time -- t11. The Microbial Zoo: How Small Is Wild? -- t12. A Home for the Wild: Architecture in the Zoo -- t13. Reconnecting Zoos to the Wild and Rethinking Dignity in Animal Conservation -- t14. Seeing the Wild in Zoos by Seeing the Humans Too -- t15. The Once and Future Rhino -- tPostscript: On Wildness and Responsibility -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aZoos have always had a troubled relationship to what is considered the “real” wild. Even the most immersive and naturalistic zoos, critics maintain, are inherently contrived and inauthentic environments. Zoo animals’ diet, care, and reproduction are under pervasive human control, with natural phenomena like disease and death kept mostly hidden from public view. Furthermore, despite their growing commitment to conservation and education, zoos are entertainment providers that respond to visitors’ expectations and preferences. What would a “wilder” zoo—one that shows the public a wider range of ecological processes—look like? Is it achievable or even desirable? What roles can or should zoos play in encouraging humanity to find meaningful connections with wild animals and places?A Wilder Kingdom is a provocative and reflective examination of the relationship between zoos and the wild. It gathers a premier set of multidisciplinary voices—from animal studies and psychology to evolutionary biology and environmental journalism—to consider the possibilities and challenges of making zoos wilder. In so doing, the contributors offer new insights into the future of the wild beyond zoos and our relationship to wild species and places across the landscape in an increasingly human-dominated era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aZoo animalsxEnvironmental enrichment. 0aZoo animalsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aZoosxManagement. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBraverman, Irus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClayton, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColodner, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDayle John, Kelsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Harry W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/